Assembling the Hardware Step by Step
Step 1 — Prepare the Raspberry Pi
Place the Raspberry Pi on a firm surface where it won't move. Insert the micro SD card into the slot on the bottom. The card should already have the operating system installed (explained later).

Step 2 — Connect the Camera
The camera connects to the port labeled "CSI" on the Raspberry Pi. This port has a small plastic clip that lifts up. Insert the camera's ribbon cable with the metal contacts facing away from the clip, and lower the clip to secure the cable. Don't pull too hard; insert it gently. Connect the other end of the cable to the camera port in the same way.

Step 3 — Connect the Display
The display uses the "DSI" port, which works exactly the same way as the camera port: clip up, ribbon cable inserted, clip lowered. You can also connect the display directly to the Raspberry Pi's power pins to draw power from there.

Step 4 — Connect the Button
The button has two wires. One wire goes to pin 18 of the Raspberry Pi (that's GPIO 18, the "input port"). The other wire goes to any pin labeled "GND" (which means ground or negative). It doesn't matter which of the two button pins goes to which side; simple buttons don't have polarity.

⚠️ Important: The Raspberry Pi pins only tolerate 3.3 volts. Never connect 5 volts directly to the GPIO pins, or you may permanently damage it.

Step 5 — Connect the thermal printer
The printer connects to the Raspberry Pi's serial port via three wires:

The Raspberry Pi's TX wire goes to the printer's RX wire.
The Raspberry Pi's RX wire goes to the printer's TX wire.
The GND wire is shared by both (they connect together to negative).

The printer needs its own separate power supply (between 5 and 9 volts, depending on the model) because it draws a lot of current when printing, and connecting it to the same power source as the Raspberry Pi can cause instability.

Step 6 — Connect the Power Supply
The 7-volt battery first passes through the buck converter, which steps it down to a stable 5 volts. This 5 volts goes to the Raspberry Pi's micro-USB port. The printer has its own power supply line, either from the battery or a separate power source.

Part 3 — Install the Software
Power on the Raspberry Pi with the screen already connected. Open a terminal window and type the following commands, one by one, waiting for each to finish before typing the next:

bashsudo apt update
sudo apt upgrade -y
sudo apt install -y python3-pip python3-venv
pip3 install picamera2 Pillow RPi.GPIO python-escpos pyserial --break-system-packages
Then copy the project files (camera.py, printer.py, main.py, config.py) into a folder, for example, ~/photobooth/src/. Also create the folder where the photos will be saved:
bashmkdir -p ~/photobooth/output
To run the program:
bashpython3 ~/photobooth/src/main.py

What is this?

It's a photo booth you built yourself from scratch. When someone presses the button, the camera takes a picture, the screen displays it, and a small printer prints it on thermal paper, just like supermarket receipts.

How does it work?

Imagine the Raspberry Pi as a tiny brain. This brain is connected to four things: a camera that sees, a screen that displays, a button that receives commands, and a printer that produces the result.

When someone presses the button, it sends an electrical signal to the brain. The brain then tells the camera, "Take a picture now." The camera obeys and sends the image back to the brain. The brain displays it on the screen for the person to see, and then sends that same image to the printer, which converts it into burned dots on thermal paper.
All of this happens in a few seconds, and it's all controlled by the Python code you wrote.

